Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["\<\
Plot Examples-2
Scatter Graphs\
\>", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7638329767037706`*^9, 3.7638330000772624`*^9}, {
   3.764246005964684*^9, 3.7642460143818665`*^9}, {3.7649181458353558`*^9, 
   3.764918160046224*^9}, {3.764977619030768*^9, 3.7649776492430973`*^9}, {
   3.7650250050376773`*^9, 3.76502503272836*^9}, 
   3.7670951034721003`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"2d0dccfa-3022-4aa8-a51e-\
2521fe290591"],

Cell["\<\
Scatter graphs are data collected pointwise. They can be collected by direct \
observations or from mathematical relations including randomly generated data.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765025040423579*^9, 
  3.76502521346146*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b17de6cd-43b5-4b1d-9646-\
280b4ca3f496"],

Cell["\<\
We will begin by sequential data. These data come one by one, that is one \
point after a previous one. Suppose you measure the viscosity of a mixture \
every after rise of two degrees beginning from an inital of 18 \[Degree]C . \
The observed viscosity value is measured after the exact temperature \
equilibrium of the mixture and heating medium and it is known that the \
viscosity is stable infinitesimally at a given constant temperature. The \
collected data will be as,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7650252209198236`*^9, 3.76502547052162*^9}, {
   3.7650272184084525`*^9, 3.765027243058117*^9}, {3.765027285008638*^9, 
   3.765027336236676*^9}, {3.7650274656328335`*^9, 3.765027479341095*^9}, 
   3.765027524333662*^9, {3.7650276275367737`*^9, 
   3.7650278555483923`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9b05547e-b472-4f21-8611-\
9da2932796b4"],

Cell[TextData[Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {
    RowBox[{"Temperature", " ", 
     RowBox[{"(", "\[Degree]C", ")"}]}], 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Nr", ".", " ", "of"}], " ", "Observation", " ", 
     RowBox[{"(", "n", ")"}]}], 
    RowBox[{"Observed", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", 
     RowBox[{"viscosity", "."}]}]},
   {
    RowBox[{"15", " ", 
     RowBox[{"(", "initial", ")"}]}], "1", "2.16"},
   {"17", "2", "3.86"},
   {"19", "3", "5.23"},
   {"21", "4", "6.11"},
   {"23", "5", "7.82"},
   {"25", "6", "9.28"},
   {"27", "7", "13.88"},
   {"29", "8", "23.77"},
   {"31", "9", "28.18"}
  },
  GridBoxDividers->{
   "Columns" -> {{True}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {{True}}, 
    "RowsIndexed" -> \
{}}]],ExpressionUUID->"64a68aeb-d022-4ee3-a6fe-85f5240b4ebf"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765025526316609*^9, 3.7650258052777534`*^9}, {
  3.765026288685811*^9, 3.765026288685811*^9}, {3.765027501685849*^9, 
  3.7650276087160254`*^9}, {3.765028013147976*^9, 3.765028013147976*^9}, {
  3.7650315377666626`*^9, 3.765031538213705*^9}, {3.765031578756291*^9, 
  3.7650316200176353`*^9}, {3.765031663192959*^9, 3.765031744044942*^9}},
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"a4e03d1f-8de7-41a1-8f72-aa0f7585e04d"],

Cell["\<\
Since, number of observation is a direct informant of the equilibrium \
temperature, we can satisfy with only two values,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765025859445179*^9, 3.7650260305324135`*^9}, 
   3.7650260896336465`*^9, {3.765027887516369*^9, 
   3.765027911624751*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e577754f-713c-4fe4-822f-\
6d77d6f9e0c6"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Number of observation,", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7650260803447895`*^9, 
  3.7650261051771016`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9001b1a7-cf0d-48c5-9935-\
af0f33839d30"],

Cell["Observed value of the viscosity.", "Item",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7650260803447895`*^9, 3.7650261453363843`*^9}, {
  3.7650279430251293`*^9, 
  3.7650279735576878`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"99aaa158-60af-40c4-b4a3-\
a4def8030929"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[BoxData[GridBox[{
   {
    StyleBox[
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Nr", ".", " ", "of"}], " ", "Observation"}],
     FontColor->GrayLevel[0]], 
    RowBox[{"Observed", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", 
     RowBox[{"viscosity", "."}]}]},
   {"1", "2.16"},
   {"2", "3.86"},
   {"3", "5.23"},
   {"4", "6.11"},
   {"5", "7.82"},
   {"6", "9.28"},
   {"7", "13.88"},
   {"8", "23.77"},
   {"9", "28.18"}
  },
  GridBoxDividers->{
   "Columns" -> {{True}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {{True}}, 
    "RowsIndexed" -> {}}]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.7650262169657*^9, {3.7650262745229025`*^9, 3.7650262935098224`*^9}, {
   3.7650279844055247`*^9, 3.7650279982664385`*^9}},
 TextAlignment->Center,ExpressionUUID->"ec380923-8f0c-44a3-9cfe-a3f0a7dce789"],

Cell["\<\
If we wish to plot Nr of Observation versus observed value, we do not need to \
provide a {temperature, observed value of the viscosity} data doublet. A data \
doublet {nr. of observation , observed value of the viscosity}  may suffice.  \
Number of observation will be the abcissa of the point (x) and the observed \
value of the viscosity will be the ordinate value.(y).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765026336645423*^9, 3.765026665500389*^9}, {
  3.765031791981862*^9, 
  3.765032148076895*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4d9a17c5-92a9-4bc8-9473-\
2d7fdec8ba2f"],

Cell["\<\
We ought to provide only a one dimensional sequential data list (a simple \
Mathematica list), the number of observation will be automatically generated \
by Mathematica as the ordinal numbers of the entered data. In computer \
science it is called the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]index\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \
of the the elements of a given list. In Mathematica list indexes are \
beginning by 1 and increasing by 1 up to the end of the entered data. One may \
access the the elements of a defined list referring the index value of a \
given element.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7650266865858517`*^9, 3.765026889260295*^9}, {
  3.7650321955281515`*^9, 3.7650321978245354`*^9}, {3.7657643885717564`*^9, 
  3.765764544750981*^9}, {3.7657645815954485`*^9, 3.765764591253434*^9}, {
  3.7657646241170807`*^9, 3.765764814780294*^9}, {3.765764950485598*^9, 
  3.765765074941174*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5df07aff-5cfb-441a-afa9-\
9e7dd873c012"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"data", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
    "2.16", ",", "3.86", ",", "5.23", ",", "6.11", ",", "7.82", ",", "9.28", 
     ",", "13.88", ",", "23.77", ",", "28.18"}], "}"}]}], ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7650268331687737`*^9, 3.76502684395436*^9}, {
  3.7650269097175055`*^9, 3.7650269730178194`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[5]:=",ExpressionUUID->"de5642bc-1bfc-4f67-aee3-209300328490"],

Cell["This list, Now we can plot this sequential data,", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765026989364942*^9, 3.7650270128413215`*^9}, {
  3.7657651053108006`*^9, 
  3.7657651570876217`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"395b924b-7754-4cac-9acd-\
0924d9fcd441"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"p1", "=", 
  RowBox[{"ListPlot", "[", "data", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765027020932685*^9, 3.7650270323779397`*^9}, {
  3.7658163648575478`*^9, 3.7658163679197907`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[6]:=",ExpressionUUID->"2647366a-382d-4330-9221-78116a4d8663"],

